%N A398029 a(n) is the number of closed binary operations on n labeled elements such that the set of ordered triples (x, y, xy) contains at least one of each of the 5 kinds of ordered triple: (a,a,a), (a,a,b), (a,b,a), (b,a,a), (a,b,c), for distinct elements a,b,c.
%C A398029 The ratio of a(n) to the total number of closed binary operations on the n elements has limit 1 - (1/e) for large n.
%C A398029 Proof of a(n) formula and limit of ratio a(n)/(n^(n^2)) are in the Pasino link paper, "Stratified Binary Operations."
%C A398029 Stratified is a word used in that paper to mean this kind of operation. It's a notion that can be said for operations and relations of any finite arity k, that they contain at least one of every kind of k-tuple. In this notion, k-ary operations are meant as a special kind of (k+1)-ary relation. Statistics of stratification might be interestingly skewed for operations among relations, but this is an ad-lib idea in preparing this sequence page.
%C A398029 The number of kinds of k-tuple is the Bell number B(k).
%H A398029 David Pasino, <a href="/A398029/a398029.pdf">Stratified Binary Operations</a>
%F A398029 a(n) = (n^n - (n-1)^n - 1)*(n^(n^2-n) - 2*(n-1)^(n^2-n) + (n-2)^(n^2-n) - 2^(n^2-n) + 2) for n > 0.
